Life and career[edit]
Born in Cambridge, Massachusetts, Epstein attended public schools in Milton, Massachusetts. He graduated from Columbia College of Columbia University in 1949 and was elected to Phi Beta Kappa. He received a Master of Arts degree from Columbia the following year and joined Doubleday and Company as an editorial trainee.
At Doubleday, he saw the need for inexpensive, well made paperbacks of the kinds of books that his classmates, many of them veterans studying on the GI Bill, were reading but couldn't afford to own in their hardcover editions. With the support of Ken McCormick, Doubleday's chief editor, he launched Anchor Books,[1] the first so-called Quality Paperbacks, which quickly became the dominant paperback format. In 1954 Anchor Books won the Carey-Thomas Award.[2]
